\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.3}{\ignorespaces Diagram showing the expanse of sea ice in the Southern Ocean. Packed ice forms closer to the continent in calmer conditions while strong oceanic currents, winds, wave action and extreme temperatures result in the formation of semi-consolidated ice in the marginal ice zone (1 to 5). Here, ice formation is highly seasonal expanding to a maximum in winter and retreating to a minimum in summer. Sea ice acts as a boundary layer influencing heat and gaseous exchange between the atmosphere and ocean. Figure taken from \textcite {Antseaice}.\relax }}{4}{figure.caption.10}%
